<div xmlns:perseus="http://www.perseus.org/meta/perseus.rdfs#" xmlns:dctype="http://purl.org/dc/dcmitype/" xmlns:tufts="http://www.tufts.edu/" xmlns:alph="http://alpheios.net/namespaces/tei" class="alpheios-lex-text_container en">
    <div class="alpheios-lex-entry" lemma-id="n4793" body-key="α">
          <b><span class="alpheios-lex-greek" lang="grc">ἵππος</span></b> : <span class="alpheios-lex-gloss">horse</span> or
            <span class="alpheios-lex-gloss">mare;</span>
          <span class="alpheios-lex-greek" lang="grc">ἄρσενες ἵπποι</span>, ‘stallions,’ <i><span class="en">Od. 13.81</span></i>
          <span class="alpheios-lex-greek" lang="grc">; θήλεες ἵπποι, ἵπποι θήλειαι, Ε 269</span>,
            <i><span class="en">Il. 11.681</span></i>; the Homeric Greeks did
          not ride horseback, but employed chariots; hence <span class="alpheios-lex-greek" lang="grc">ἵπποι</span>,  oftener <span class="alpheios-lex-greek" lang="grc">ἵππω</span>, <span class="alpheios-lex-gloss">span, chariot</span>, alone or w. <span class="alpheios-lex-greek" lang="grc">ἅρμα</span>, <i><span class="en">Il.
            12.120</span></i>; freq. <span class="alpheios-lex-greek" lang="grc">ἵπποισιν καὶ
            ὄχεσφιν,</span>
          <i><span class="en">Il. 12.114</span></i>, <span class="alpheios-lex-greek" lang="grc">
            119; ἐξ</span> or <span class="alpheios-lex-greek" lang="grc">ἀφ᾽ ἵππων ἀποβῆναι, Γ
            265</span>, <i><span class="en">Il. 5.13</span></i>; of
          chariotmen as opposed to infantry, <i><span class="en">Od.
            14.267</span></i>, <i><span class="en">Il. 2.554</span></i>, <i><span class="en">Il. 16.167</span></i>, <i><span class="en">Il.
            18.153</span></i>.</div> <div class="alpheios-lex-footnotes en"> </div>
    <div class="alpheios-lex-alph-source">From <u>
            <u>A Homeric Dictionary</u>
        </u> (Georg Autenrieth, New York, Harper and Brothers, 1891) </div>
</div>